<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">sport of us which entertained the old people who were seated upon the top of their houses enj<span class="AddHand-editors">[oy]</span>ing the cool of the forenoon.  The Dogs also assaulted us and were very troublesome.  We therefore did not stop at this Village which consists of only Sixty huts<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  We passed on to the last Village which is the principal.  It contains one hundred &amp; thirty huts.  Here we found M<sup>r</sup> Charles M<sup>c</sup>Kenzie and M<sup>r</sup> James Caldwell both in the Employ of the North west company.  They left <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Riviere de la Sourie</span> with an assortment of Goods for trade in May last.  The Natives very readily conducted us to the hut where our friends resided &#8212; which was that of the Great Chief of the Village.  The chief himself who is <span class="AddHand-author">stiled</span> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">La Birgne</span> was absent on a visit to a camp of Schians settling the preliminaries of a Peace with that nation who were tented to days march to the South East.  Here we met with not attention<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  This is a proud haughty nation who think themselves superior to Every other people.  Were it not for the absolute necessity of procuring arms and ammunition to guard against their enemies no white<span class="AddHand-author">s</span> could remain among them.  The men of this nation are remarkably stout and well proportion-</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">-ed</p>

